    <body>
      <div xml:id="NA276-kiḷavi">
        <p type="edition">itu pakaṟkuṟi vantu peyarun talaimakaṉai (ET: tōḻi) ulakiyal colliyatu.</p>
        <p type="translation" xml:lang="en">This is how [the confidante] spoke about the nature of the world to HIM who returned, having come to the day tryst.</p>
        </div>
      <div xml:id="NA276">
        <lg type="edition">
<l>            kōṭu tuvaiyāk kōḷvāy nāyoṭu</l>
<l>            kāṭutēr nacaiiya vayamāṉ vēṭṭu</l>
<l>            vayavar makaḷi reṉṟi yāyiṟ</l>
<l>            kuṟavar makaḷirēṅ kuṉṟukeḻu koṭiyēñ</l>
<l>            cēṇō ṉiḻaitta neṭunkāṟ kaḻutiṟ </l>
<l>            kāṉa maññai kaṭci cēkkuṅ</l>
<l>            kallakat tatuvem mūrē cellātu</l>
<l>            cēntaṉai ceṉmati nīyē perumalai</l>
<l>            vāṅkamai paḻuniya naṟavuṇṭu</l>
<l>            vēṅkai muṉṟiṟ kuravaiyuṅ kaṇṭē.</l>
            </lg>
        <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>If you say we are the women of men strong in</l>
<l rend="indent">hunting the strong stag, that yearn for searching the wilderness</l>
<l rend="indent">with [their] dogs with seizing mouths, sounding the horn noisily,</l>
<l>– we are women of the hill people,</l>
<l rend="indent4">we [are] creeper-women from the hills.</l>
<l>Our village [is] inside the stones,</l>
<l rend="indent">where the forest peacock rests in [its] nest</l>
<l rend="indent2">by the long-legged platform raised by the [field-]guardian.</l>
<l>Rest without going [and] go you, having tasted the toddy</l>
<l rend="indent2">become mellow in the bent bamboo on the big mountain and</l>
<l rend="indent2">having seen the Kuravai dance in the front yard with the Vēṅkai tree.</l>
        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
